Lai has been described by Beijing as a "dangerous separatist" for his past declarations in favour of Taiwan's independence, although since then he had softened his rhetoric and committed himself to maintaining the status quo, a balance that took over Taiwan's sovereignty, without declaring formal independence. But on the day of the settlement, in the Presidential Palace of Tapei, Lai, former vice-president, presented together with the new vice-president, Hsiao Bi-khim, did not spare Beijing criticism.
<h2> The word "democracy" pronounced 31 times </h2>
Lai invited China to "stop its political and military intimidation" and thanked the Taiwanese for resisting the influence of "external forces". "I also want to thank my fellow citizens for having refused to let themselves be influenced by external forces and for defending democracy resolutely," he said, adding - citing for more than 31 times the word 'democracy' - that "the glorious era of Taiwanese democracy has arrived". "The future of the Republic of China will be decided by its 23 million inhabitants," said Lai, referring not only to geopolitical security but also to the importance of Taiwan as one of the most advanced economies of the world and the first global supplier of semiconductors >.
&nbsp;
Words that warmed the minds in Beijing. And the first real retaliation was that of the Chinese social network Weibo, equivalent to the X platform, which immediately blocked the hashtags related to the inauguration. Before the establishment of Lai, the Beijing Office for Business in Taiwan, which deals with issues through the Strait, said that " Taiwan independence and peace through the Strait" were "like fire and water".
<h2>Congratulations of Washington</h2>
Meanwhile, American Secretary of State Antony Blinken congratulated the newly established, saying that he eagerly awaits that Washington and Taipei maintain "peace and stability through the Taiwan Strait". In addition to greeting Lai, "we also congratulate the people of Taiwan for showing once again the strength of their robust and resilient democratic system," Blinken said in a note.
&nbsp;
"The partnership between the American people and Taiwan, rooted in democratic values, continues to expand and deepen through commercial, economic, cultural and interpersonal ties," added the US top diplomat. "We are eager to work with President Lai and with all Taiwan's political spectrum to promote our shared interests and values." Statements arriving at the time China also made it known that the intention to sanction three U.S. defense companies for their weapons sales in Taiwan.&nbsp;

